'''Muhammad Hardyman bin Abdul Lamit''' is a [[Brunei]]an [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Kota Ranger FC]] of the [[Brunei Super League]] as a [[Midfielder (association football)|midfielder]]. He has represented Brunei in football and also in [[futsal]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Brunei set for AFC futsal qualifiers|url=http://www.bt.com.bn/sport/2008/02/23/brunei_set_for_afc_futsal_qualifiers|date=23 February 2008|publisher=[[The Brunei Times]]|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref>
Hardyman previously played for [[QAF FC]] ever since their entry into the [[Brunei Premier League|B-League]] back in [[2003 Brunei Premier League|2003]]. He won the Bruneian championship three times in a row with QAF, along with two [[Brunei League Cups|League Cups]] and two [[Brunei Super Cup|Super Cups]].<ref>{{cite web |title=QAF FC a victory away from a hat-trick of titles|url=http://www.bt.com.bn/sport-national/2010/02/04/qaf-fc-victory-away-hat-trick-titles|date=4 February 2010|publisher=The Brunei Times|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref> When the club declined to continue playing in the [[Brunei Super League]] in [[2015 Brunei Super League|2015]], he transferred to [[Jerudong FC]] along with many of his QAF teammates, finishing sixth in the table that year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indera SC ready to defend DST Super League crown|url=http://www.bt.com.bn/sports-national/2015/03/27/indera-sc-ready-defend-dst-super-league-crown|date=27 March 2015|publisher=The Brunei Times|accessdate=27 April 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414203651/http://www.bt.com.bn/sports-national/2015/03/27/indera-sc-ready-defend-dst-super-league-crown|archivedate=14 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
Hardyman stayed with Jerudong FC in [[2016 Brunei Super League|2016]] after the club suffered a mass exodus of players. He eventually was appointed club captain.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lun Bawang finally in win column|url=http://www.bt.com.bn/sports-national/2016/09/19/lun-bawang-finally-win-column|date=19 September 2016|publisher=The Brunei Times|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> He scored against [[Tabuan U21]] on 9 April in a 2–2 draw to help his team gain their first point of the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jerudong fight back to draw with Tabuan U-21|url=http://www.bt.com.bn/sports-national/2016/04/10/jerudong-fight-back-draw-tabuan-u-21|date=10 April 2016|publisher=The Brunei Times|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref>
==International career== Hardyman made appearances for the [[Brunei national under-21 football team|Brunei under-21s]] in the first two [[Hassanal Bolkiah Trophy]] tournaments in [[2002 Hassanal Bolkiah Trophy|2002]] and [[2005 Hassanal Bolkiah Trophy|2005]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Hassan al Bolkiah Trophy (Brunei) 2002|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bolkiah02.html|date=22 June 2005|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=ASEAN U-21 Championship 2005 (Piala Hassanal Bolkiah)|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/asean-u21-05.html|date=22 June 2005|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref>
Hardyman made his international debut for [[Brunei national football team|Brunei]] at the [[2004 AFC Asian Cup qualification]] match against [[Myanmar national football team|Myanmar]] on 23 March 2003. He was a second-half substitute in place of [[Fadlin Galawat]] as the Wasps lost the game 5–0.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brunei Darussalam 0 : 5 Myanmar|url=http://www.pakfootball.org/match_report.php?m=681489|date=|publisher=Pakistan Football Federation|accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref> He then played for Brunei while the national team was represented by his then club QAF FC in 2006 and 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brudirect.com/DailyInfo/News/Archive/Nov06/101106/nite26.htm|title=QAF FC For AFF Challenge |publisher=[[Borneo Bulletin]]|date=7 February 2007|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201161623/http://www.brudirect.com/DailyInfo/News/Archive/Nov06/101106/nite26.htm|archivedate=1 December 2008|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Brunei get green light to play|url=http://www.bt.com.bn/local_sport/2009/03/10/brunei_get_green_light_to_play|date=10 March 2009|publisher=The Brunei Times|accessdate=16 May 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127170844/http://www.bt.com.bn/local_sport/2009/03/10/brunei_get_green_light_to_play|archivedate=27 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
Hardyman is also a member of the [[Brunei national futsal team]] and has represented Brunei since 2003, his first appearances were at the [[2003 AFF Futsal Championship]] in [[Kuantan]], [[Malaysia]].
